As an aspiring designer for ani/games, I actually have a lot of feelings about SM's character designs in particular and how visually iconic they are! They were a really big inspiration when I was doing concept and character work with @BlueRoseSonata for wip game Ohohohojou-sama

But despite the simplification and his personal style, ALL THE CHARACTERS ARE STILL INSTANTLY RECOGNIZABLE AND FAMILIAR. A certain degree of "off model" in animation can actually highlight a Really Good Design, bc it's recognizable as That Character across a variety of styles.

Like, Ando's episodes of Sailor Moon got flack for being simplified and how he drew all the characters in a way that like... I personally really like this, they're all very soft and rounded and bouncy feeling. I like it a lot more than some of the more "angular" artists.

I think for a film it's more important to keep a consistent visual style throughout as much as possible. TV shows allow visual experimentation via personal expression episode to episode, and as long as the design is iconic enough to be recognizable it's not an issue.

I think traditional animation for TV having a tendency to go "off model" in stylization was actually really fun, and I don't think it's an inherent flaw at all :( Like the thread I RT'd said, it shows the personal touches of artists. I like cartoons that feel organic like that.

Probably my fav example is Sailor Moon bc it has SO many distinctive styles for a series and because it's just my favourite in general! My personal underrated fav of SM's list of ADs is Masahiro Ando, he gets a lot of flack for how "off model" his episodes are, but I love them https://t.co/8nODQpynSX

One reason it's wild is the obvious "people just LOVE to make judgments about industries they have no experience or knowledge of", but the other is that it's always been legitimately one of my fav things to do w trad animation to try and identify artists who worked on an episode.

It is Wild to me that people (always not actually animators, or genuinely interested in Becoming animators or Understanding what it's like to be one) get legitimately really angry about shows going off model sometimes

@PuddiCure like, both penguindrum & the utena film got me used to how intense ikuni could be when he wasn't being restricted by producing a kid's anime timeslot show for toei before i touched the anime series, it was a trial by fire but also made utena feel way more Slow in comparison!

@PuddiCure it's also funny bc my order of experience with ikuhara works was like
sailor moon as a child & rewatching in my teens/early 20s -> utena film one night at 3 am -> penguindrum anime as it aired -> utena anime -> yurikuma, which in and of itself is a huge rollercoaster of emotions

@PuddiCure which ends up meaning that like... even if it's overall comparable, penguindrum is a VERY rapid roller coaster of those emotions and you do NOT have anywhere near as much recovery time as utena gives you, yknow?

That's the moral I want to get at, that even if you're living alone and wfh all the time and not Seeing People, depression can make it really easy to drop things that feel "unnecessary" when alone. But if those things help you feel good about yourself, you deserve to do them.

But I recently started trying to do it again after giving a friend product advice bc it reminded me, "hey, I really liked that. I think I miss it. Maybe i deserve to do things that make me feel good about myself, even if I'm the only one around to see it."

Like a more reasonable, relatable example might be that I also had an in-depth skincare routine, too, not bc I'm scared of aging but because I GENUINELY enjoyed how it made me feel (fresh & pretty), and during the pandemic I dropped it! I stopped making myself feel good!

Maybe "my routine made my dr ask if I might have OCD and I had to explain it just stems from not being able to afford dental care as a child" isn't the best venue for this but like. It got me thinking about how just bc I'm alone doesn't mean I don't deserve more in-depth care?

Not just mentally yucky but like earlier this morning when I put my mask on to go check the mail it was before I'd brushed my teeth & had breakfast so I got hit with morning breath and now even tho I'm alone my stress about dental hygiene is back in full force lmao

I went from 2x a day brushing teeth, brushing tongue **with special zinc-including paste for your tongue lmao**, 2 different mouthwashes to be EXTRA thorough, and flossing, and like. Is that a bit excessive? Sure! But Just Brushing/some flossing has made me feel real yucky lately

Regret: I have a lot of anxiety abt dental hygiene so for the longest time I had a supremely in depth routine but a combo of depression + total isolation due to moving away during a pandemic got me to strip it to the bare essentials bc i mean... "why bother when alone" right

Re: the milk powder in the marinade, I personally hate how reconstituted milk powder tastes as a drink but it's GREAT for marinades and baking because you can easily mix up buttermilk on the fly if you have an acid handy like vinegar or lemon juice!!

Veggie sides I'd probably recommend are pickled red onions if you have the spoons to make a batch or can find something comparable at the store https://t.co/GaV3wDXDby and sarson ka saag which you can make with spinach and/or mustard greens!!

You end up with something crispy on the outside + soft on the inside that's pretty yummy. I had it with rice, would also be delicious w naan, and you could even use the leftovers to cook in masala for a curry

I used just a TINY amount of salt in the marinade to enhance flavours largely bc I was doing it overnight and tofu absorbs flavours VERY easily and didn't want it too salty. So I tasted it after frying and lightly salted it then too

It was VERY simple, though. Even firm tofu is soft and easy to slice so good for ppl with hand pain, marinade it in a mixture of milk powder, water, vinegar or lemon juice, and tandoori masala/garlic powder/salt/other misc seasoning. Then I tossed in flour and fried it c:

Made somethin yummy today when scrounging in my kitchen: tandoori tofu!! I always have tofu on hand, same with milk powder in the freezer for baking, and I like indian cuisine a lot so I have a good variety of basic seasoning to channel those ~flavours~, so ymmv wrt staples

what i started doing to try and counteract this is with certain chara designs i'll sketch the character bald with a very rough placement guideline and then jump straight to painting the hair in from there to try and see how the shape reads in colour before i commit to lineart

bc when i first started doing chara commissions i would do sketches and the hair would look really nice to my eye, flowy lines and shapes - but then i'd go in for cleanup and colouring and suddenly it would lose it's flow, look more blocky, yknow?

improving silhouette is a common ground btwn them i think, while drawing i think i want to more often block out a shape against the bg so i can see how the character 'reads' overall in terms of contrast/composition/negative space. i noticed a struggle w this most often w hair tbh

i know learning how to effectively simplify my drawing can help me get better w painting, but i still feel torn btwn paths i wanna take to learn bc like. drawing is so focused on lines, implying texture thru the weight of them etc, vs painting which is more shape and edge control

tfw i want to be able to paint in a textured realistic style but i also want to be able to draw strikingly simplified art and i'm constantly torn btwn learning how to render in a more detailed way and learning how to just boil s/t down to its most simple shapes/lines

I know I’m probably preaching to the choir here but remember to be understanding and open minded about why people may be continuing to use these platforms, options are limited and even with alternatives, it’s still so few and you don’t want all your eggs in one basket etc
Marginalized creators (queer, other countries, etc) & those who create content that’s NSFW or counter culture are hit especially hard by it, even moreso if any of those categories overlap

I think it's the team aspect of visdev for animation/games that really calls to me - the thought of being able to make choices and come up with concepts from scratch but also having a team that can balance eachother's struggles/help eachother to shine as a whole

Also while typing this out I had a moment where I found myself laughing and going "wait, and I want to go into VISDEV?" because so much of that is making decisions and ideas. But I also know there's a lot of building on OTHER PEOPLE'S work ie not always 100% from scratch

It's such an interesting change, tho, because when I was younger I would CONSTANTLY spend my time sketching and starting new things and never ever finishing anything bc I was too impatient and wanted something New!

- it ends up being the thing I struggle with most, especially when I'm doing paid work - bc every choice feels so vital to the success or failure in terms of making a satisfying piece for clients. Lineart and simple colouring is "easy" bc I've already made the hardest decisions

From a more brain sciencey pov I wonder if it's because as my process for lineart & colouring has become a lot more streamlined those are a bit easier and "brain off", but because ideation and sketching require CONSTANT DECISION MAKING (every single line placement is a Choice!)-

Starting the ideation and sketching process is always the biggest hurdle with me and my brain, I swear. I love making art so much but I've found over the years that now that I've found how to get comfy finishing pieces, I always get tripped up and struggle to *start* new ones

Time that I can solely devote to fanart ideas bopping around in my brain, learning new skills, and even developing new projects

Because of that I RARELY give myself solid chunks of time to just draw what I feel like for myself or study and seriously internalize new skill knowledge - learning Blender basics over the holidays made me realize I need that freedom more often for myself

The reason I mention adhd/chronic pain is bc honestly at this point, for the longest time now my “days off” from work have all revolved around things like resting bc of pain that keeps me from drawing and/or catching up on tasks that have been neglected bc of hyperfocus/avoidance

I guess I’m essentially introducing a way to earn PTO in a way that works for me as a freelancer with adhd and chronic pain lmao. Anyways for every 2 days where I meet my paid art work hourly quota or complete a piece and send it off I earn 1 free day for whatever I want to draw

I’m bad at making myself follow regimented work routines which means I also struggle to block off “vacation/personal work time” outside of Christmas so I’m trying a new system where I can bank up days off to draw whatever I want all day

So remember how I said I previously only used YT to archive my Twitch VODs? I would use Twitch's built in feature to export content from there to Youtube, and it automatically set the thumbnails/description FOR me, and I didn't bother to change it bc it was a Personal archive.

Because of that transparency, you may be wondering where the theft accusation comes in. So was I! I was gobsmacked to find out someone was accusing me of it, because one of many reasons I use 3D software like Daz and now Blender to craft my own references is to AVOID that mess.

While the Twitch streams in which I worked on this piece are vaulted, I did get CSP to record a timelapse for most of the process that you can still watch on Youtube, and I'm really transparent about my drawing process - including use of 3D models, etc https://t.co/1LesDn59Ai

One illustration that I streamed my progress on extensively via Twitch and archived to YT was a piece for @soleilofylisse of her D&D character, Fia, from our Curse of Strahd campaign, commemorating their final moments. It was really personal and meant a lot to both of us!! https://t.co/jW6g6zFd2X

Those archival videos have since been vaulted because I wanted to ~rebrand~ as a vtuber and make content for Youtube, and hiding my old inexperienced Twitch stream archives just seemed like the right idea - they were disorganized, I didn't give them custom thumbnails, etc

A lot of you know that before I swapped to streaming on Youtube, I was a Twitch streamer! I hit affiliate and everything, it was very cool. I mainly would stream art, but occasionally things like D2 raids and eventually Genshin Impact, and I would use my Youtube as an archive.

We're seeing technology and coding developed specifically to achieve certain specific looks and feels, getting proof of concept of that tech in animated shorts and later seeing it show up in larger scale productions. IT'S JUST ALL SO COOL

I guess that's one of the things that always got me abt the industry shifting from 2D to 3D - the thing w 2D animation is if you can draw it, you can make it move, you can animate, any style. With 3D, you're limited by the tech. Over time tho we're seeing more tech limits pushed!

In general, I'm really hyped to see more and more studios experiment and push the boundaries and limitations of 3D over the upcoming years. The quest to bring the imagination to the screen and bend the technology to support that is so exciting

I'm so curious, now, what Tangled would visually look like if it had been made in 2021 onwards - that goal of a 'living painting' is clearly something more technologically feasible now, and I bet it would be just GORGEOUS. Just imagining the brushwork makes my heart flutter lol

Now we have the bold, experimental comic-inspired stylization of Spiderverse and Mitchells vs the Machines, the painterly 'living concept art' feeling to the rendering of figures in Arcane blended with 2D visual effects... 3D animation has evolved SO MUCH over just a few years!!

After Tangled wrapped, Disney started production on Paperman which was a breathtaking example of what could be accomplished when attempting to blur the lines btwn 2D and 3D visual styles, pushing the boundaries of what ppl expect 3D ani to look like

The thing is, back before 2010 that was still experimental to the point of being daunting even for a studio like Disney! It ended up visually revamped into something more traditional for 3D animation, but def still had the charm of 2D thanks to artists like Glen Keane

Also, backpedaling to Tangled because it's one of my favourite films - did you know that originally a big goal for the film was to make it look like a rococo painting brought to life? The footage is short and poor quality, but you can see some here https://t.co/1ltD7ahdkg

Moana in general is a gorgeous film and technically innovative on a lot of levels - the hair and the water animation alone are things I could excitedly ramble about for hours - but the way Maui's tattoos were 2D animation incorporated into a 3D feature was experimental & amazing

You know what 3D Disney feature DID have sequences on par with Almost There tho??? MOANA!!!! Maui's tattoos and the cutout dancing figures and bg elements when things get extra trippy are all absolutely superb and I remember it really standing out to me! https://t.co/g2UeI19jdm

Disney's Tangled was the film that got me excited again about the thought of working on Disney features someday even if they DID shift over exclusively to 3D, but it still didn't have any scene as visually experimental as PATF did in Almost There.

One example that I absolutely ADORE and has stuck w me for years is "Almost There" from PATF - I was so disappointed by the shift Disney made to exclusively 3D features after PATF bc we simply didn't see sequences like this for a long time https://t.co/kbvvrBoPG7

This is something that, as 3D ani evolves more and style experimentation deviates from expected shaders/rendering style, is becoming more common, and it makes me v happy!! I think TVTropes has this kind of thing coined as the Disney Acid Sequence, bc they're often kinda trippy

While my pc runs through some things I'm thinking abt experimental stylization in 3D films again and I wanna ramble a bit: something I love that is VERY common in 2D animation and was not as common/noticeable in early 3D animation is sequences w sudden dramatic art style shifts
@originalsinnerr same ;; like do I want to see more of this thing that I liked visually? yes! do i want that at the expense of all other innovation and experimentation? NO!!!!! NOT AT ALL, PLEASE,

basically, if you struggle with ADD/ADHD/etc and you've been raw dogging life on no stimulants and you have a PCP, I highly recommend talking to them about stimulant medication. I'm on the lowest vyvanse dose and I feel like I went from being a zombie to actually able to function

I've been feeling for so long like I was barely getting by and each day was feeling harder in some way, I'm tempering expectations that it won't ALWAYS be this significant of a difference but it feels like I finally have something that might help me cope in the long run and like

I'm sorry for rambling so much, just. For the past 3 years my dr&I have been trying to treat my ADD w/o stim meds bc of my naturally high anxiety and being on watch for possible mania while we tried SSRIs for my depression, I was barely getting by and the pandemic made it worse

literally one of the first things i did when i realized how huge of a difference it was in terms of wakefulness was message em bc i knew she understood from when she started adderall just to be like "IS THIS HOW NEUROTYPICALS ALWAYS GET TO FEEL??????????"

I don't know yet how much of a change it is for focus specifically yet but being able to think clearly without my brain feeling like it's all cluttered and jumbled will definitely help w my focus struggles over the long term

i'm able to THINK, i don't have OBNOXIOUS BRAIN FOG, i can MENTALLY PROCESS THINGS??????? It's such a huge change from 1 stupid pill that it makes me want to start crying but I'm really easy to cry so that's normal

I used to drink insane amounts of concentrated black coffee in highschool to be even half this alert before noon, to the point where it gave me racing heartbeat and aggravated my chronic panic attacks severely - 1 vyvanse and my hr is only a tiny bit elevated but I'm AWAKE

I've read a lot about people waking up early, taking their ADHD stimulant med, and then napping until it kicks in - but mine started actually working to wake me up before I could fall asleep again which is a VERY VERY GOOD THING FOR ME, JUST NOT WHAT I WAS EXPECTING

Day 1 on Vyvanse, took it as soon as I woke up and the sheer difference it made in terms of my chronic struggles w lethargy and sleep inertia is insane - I put it on my bedside table and popped my dosage as soon as my first alarm went off, expecting my usual "I fall asleep again"

the problem is basically that i very much do not want to overwhelm said loved ones and potentially ruin something for them, whether that is merely short term or long term! because i know that sometimes, even with the best intentions, i can end up doing that.

like, it's not ESSENTIAL. you are fully capable of getting an exemplary utena experience w/o tracing all the threads that ended up woven into that narrative tapestry to their original bobbins, yknow? but utena is a major hyperfixation for me and i really want to share EVERYTHING

i am not ashamed to admit that i initially only picked up hermann hesse's work to read because of utena and was delighted to find that i actually enjoyed demian a lot more than i initially thought i would

i desperately want to get loved ones into utena but the problem is that "getting loved ones into utena" means me pulling up an intimidating trigger list and an even more intimidating recommended reading list of meta as well as the literature that inspired ikuni in the first place

like, there's obviously so much more to it as a story than that! it's hard to talk about "what utena is about" and settle on one singular message that truly encompasses everything. but the concept of "breaking free" comes close, and it's s/t that appears in all his work.

the fact that remembering utena was what really tipped me over into being emotional about art and the limitations imposed upon our innate human desire to dream/create by a capitalist society feels really fitting when it's an anime abt breaking free of societal limitations in gen

@originalsinnerr i spend so much time drawing to buy my groceries and keep my internet on that outside of that, i just Think about what i'd like to draw while i play video games or do chores bc they let me turn my brain off for a bit.

@originalsinnerr Honestly... if I didn't have to work just to keep food in my stomach and bills paid I'd want to just spend my time helping friends bring stories to life ;_; friends will comment that I almost never draw outside of work or studying and its like. Well, because I can't Afford to aha

i want to imagine a world where money isn't an issue and artists are able to collaborate on projects like that, on that scale, that level of artistry and meaning, ALL THE TIME but. but we're limited, by time and budget cuts and simply not having the money or opportunities.

idk. op just got me thinking about that - it's a fact about ikuhara's career that's stuck with me for the past decade or so, that if you find yourself in that kind of position, with that budget, that reach, that influence - you shouldn't take it for granted.

the thing is, i think a lot of that 'difficult' reputation prob comes from the attitude he's approached projects with since the 90s: that he won't have another opportunity like this in his lifetime, so he better go all out. that he only gets one chance to tell this story right.

between 1999, when the utena film came out, and 2011, when penguindrum came out, he didn't helm direction of a single anime series. and progressively, every chance he's had at a show has been shorter and shorter. he's seen as difficult to work with.

i think a lot about how revolutionary girl utena, an anime with a very fitting name considering the impact it's had, ikuhara used his success from sailor moon & scouted a team to make something as perfect to the vision as possible bc he felt like he'd never have that chance again https://t.co/OmdH7oKstf

@spiderlilywrite Yeah!! The way I see it is like - the more people in freelance/indie creative fields who raise the pricing standard, the better things get for ALL of us, as well as just knowing I have gained so much joy from independent fiction, free and paid, and want writers to be appreciated!

@spiderlilywrite (I say this bc I feel like for people who are doing it alongside other jobs, it can feel like a 'cheap side gig' - it CAN be that, but consider that you could be writing things for YOURSELF during that time. How much money is worth diverting your creative attention?)

@spiderlilywrite (Also, like - for people who are doing this alongside another job? I actually highly recommend pricing higher. Your time is EXTREMELY limited when juggling jobs and you should treat it as having a higher value even if your confidence isn't there yet!)

@spiderlilywrite Plus - there is no harm from testing the waters by offering commissions at a higher price. If nobody from your current audience is able to afford it, depending on your financial situation you can either keep it where it is or adjust it accordingly, or offer discount periods

i'm sure there are other delicious recipes, especially ones more complex than mine, but mine is very budget friendly and simple enough that i can comfortably do it even when i'm feeling under the weather ;u; as long as i can slice onions & stir them occasionally, i can make it!

one reason that i love liver is because since i was a teenager i've had chronic issues with severe anemia - and liver is one of THE richest sources of it. finding a way to prepare it that was tasty was vital for me LOL

because of how quickly liver cooks compared to how slow onions caramelize, i like to do onions first and then nestle liver in between, flipping after a minute or two to cook the other side for the same length before serving!! it's very tender and savory and melts in your mouth!

a great thing about the onions & concentrated bouillon is that because you have a lot of control over how much liquid is added as opposed to a carton/can/cup of broth or stock, you can make a VERY flavourful beef+onion gravy without the need for adding any starchy thickeners

that's why caramelized onions make such a good pairing! my liver & onions recipe is just slices of beef liver, a bunch of onions sliced very thin, concentrated beef bouillon, and seasonings of your choosing (i recommend garlic, and all purpose seasoning for ultra simplicity)

my personal tips on cooking liver:
- it cooks VERY quickly, so don't leave it in the pan too long! it'll become very tough!
- since it's not as mildly flavoured as other beef cuts, it's best paired with other very strong flavours that dominate it, especially if you aren't fond
i am a BIG fan and upseller of organ meats i'm ngl

also beef liver is super nutritious, and really affordable compared to other cuts of beef!!! when you buy liver, you're guaranteeing that it doesn't go to waste, since it's such an unpopular (MISUNDERSTOOD) choice compared to other cuts!!
